The Cooley-Tukey FFT algorithm is a divide-and-conquer algorithm that factorizes the DFT into smaller DFTs of size `n/2`. Here is one possible implementation of the Cooley-Tukey FFT algorithm:

```c++
void fft(std::vector<std::complex<double>>& x) {
    int n = x.size();
    if (n <= 1) {
        // base case: nothing to do
        return;
    } else if (n % 2 != 0) {
        // error: FFT algorithm requires input size to be a power of 2
        throw std::invalid_argument("Input size must be a power of 2");
    } else {
        // divide
        std::vector<std::complex<double>> even(n / 2);
        std::vector<std::complex<double>> odd(n / 2);
        for (int i = 0; i < n / 2; ++i) {
            even[i] = x[2 * i];
            odd[i] = x[2 * i + 1];
        }
        // conquer
        fft(even);
        fft(odd);
        // combine
        for (int k = 0; k < n / 2; ++k) {
            std::complex<double> t = std::polar(1.0, -2 * M_PI * k / n) * odd[k];
            x[k] = even[k] + t;
            x[k + n / 2] = even[k] - t;
        }
    }
}
```

This implementation takes a vector `x` of complex numbers and performs the forward FFT in-place. The input size `n` must be a power of 2. The algorithm works as follows:

1. If the input size `n` is 0 or 1, there is nothing to do and the function returns.
2. If the input size `n` is odd, this is an error and the function throws an exception.
3. Otherwise, the input vector `x` is split into two smaller vectors `even` and `odd` containing the even-indexed and odd-indexed elements of `x`, respectively.
4. The FFT is recursively applied to `even` and `odd`.
5. The results of the FFT on `even` and `odd` are combined to obtain the FFT of `x`. This is done by computing the twiddle factor (a complex exponential) for each frequency bin in the second half of `x`, multiplying it by the corresponding element of `odd`, and adding it to the corresponding element of `even`. The same computation is done for the other half of `x`, using the negative of the twiddle factor.

Note that this implementation uses the `std::polar()` function to compute the twiddle factor in polar form, which is more numerically stable than computing the real and imaginary parts separately. Also note that this implementation assumes that the input vector `x` has length `n` equal to a power of 2. If the length is not a power of 2, the input vector can be padded with zeros to the next power of 2.
